/*==========================================================
1ï¸âƒ£ INTRODUCTION TO DBMS
==========================================================*/

-- Data:
-- Raw facts (numbers, text, symbols) without meaning
-- Example: 101, Anup, 90

-- Database:
-- Organized collection of related data
-- Stored in tables for easy access & management

-- File System vs DBMS:
-- File System: Redundancy, no security, hard to manage
-- DBMS: Less redundancy, security, concurrency, backup

-- DBMS:
-- Software to store, retrieve, manage data efficiently
-- Examples: MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL

-- Applications of DBMS:
-- Banking, Railway reservation, College systems, E-commerce

-- Data Abstraction (3 Levels):
-- Physical level   â†’ How data stored
-- Logical level    â†’ What data stored
-- View level       â†’ What user sees

-- 3-Tier Architecture:
-- Presentation layer (UI)
-- Application layer (Logic)
-- Database layer (DBMS)


/*==========================================================
2ï¸âƒ£ TYPES OF DATABASE
==========================================================*/

-- Hierarchical Database â†’ Tree structure
-- Network Database      â†’ Graph structure
-- Relational Database   â†’ Tables (Most popular)
-- NoSQL Database        â†’ Big data, flexible schema


/*==========================================================
3ï¸âƒ£ DATA MODELS
==========================================================*/

-- Data Model:
-- Structure of data + relationship + constraints

-- Types:
-- Object-based model (ER Model)
-- Record-based model (Relational Model)

-- ER Model:
-- Entity       â†’ Real-world object (Student)
-- Attribute    â†’ Property (RollNo, Name)
-- Relationship â†’ Connection between entities

-- ER Diagram:
-- Rectangle â†’ Entity
-- Oval      â†’ Attribute
-- Diamond   â†’ Relationship

-- Relational Model:
-- Data stored in tables (rows & columns)


/*==========================================================
4ï¸âƒ£ RDBMS
==========================================================*/

-- RDBMS:
-- Relational Database Management System
-- Data stored in tables with relations

-- Table Components:
-- Row (Tuple)      â†’ Single record
-- Column (Field)   â†’ Attribute
-- Cell             â†’ Intersection

-- Intension:
-- Structure of table (schema)

-- Extension:
-- Actual data stored in table

-- Keys:
-- Primary Key  â†’ Unique + Not Null
-- Foreign Key  â†’ References primary key
-- Candidate Keyâ†’ Possible primary keys
-- Super Key    â†’ Set of attributes for uniqueness

-- Normalization:
-- Remove redundancy & anomalies

-- 1NF â†’ Atomic values
-- 2NF â†’ No partial dependency
-- 3NF â†’ No transitive dependency

-- Denormalization:
-- Combine tables to improve performance
-- Used when READ is more frequent


/*==========================================================
5ï¸âƒ£ SQL (STRUCTURED QUERY LANGUAGE)
==========================================================*/

-- SQL Commands:
-- DDL â†’ CREATE, ALTER, DROP
-- DML â†’ INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
-- DQL â†’ SELECT
-- DCL â†’ GRANT, REVOKE
-- TCL â†’ COMMIT, ROLLBACK

-- Operators:
-- Arithmetic â†’ + - * /
-- Comparison â†’ = != > <
-- Logical    â†’ AND OR NOT

-- Aggregate Functions:
-- COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(), MIN(), MAX()

-- Sub Query:
-- Query inside another query
-- Used with SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE


/*==========================================================
6ï¸âƒ£ TRANSACTIONS & CONCURRENCY CONTROL
==========================================================*/

-- Transaction:
-- Set of operations executed as a single unit

-- ACID Properties:
-- Atomicity  â†’ All or nothing
-- Consistencyâ†’ Valid state
-- Isolation  â†’ No interference
-- Durability â†’ Permanent save

-- Schedule:
-- Serial   â†’ One transaction at a time
-- Parallel â†’ Multiple transactions together

-- Isolation Levels:
-- Read Uncommitted
-- Read Committed
-- Repeatable Read
-- Serializable

-- Serializability:
-- Ensures same result as serial execution

-- Locking Protocols:
-- Shared Lock    â†’ Read
-- Exclusive Lock â†’ Write


/*==========================================================
7ï¸âƒ£ QUERY OPTIMIZATION
==========================================================*/

-- Goal:
-- Reduce query execution time

-- Techniques:
-- Proper indexing
-- Avoid SELECT *
-- Use WHERE clause
-- Use joins efficiently

-- Indexing:
-- Improves search speed
-- Types:
-- Primary Index
-- Secondary Index
-- Composite Index

-- B-Tree:
-- Balanced tree
-- Used for indexing

-- B+ Tree:
-- Data only at leaf nodes
-- Faster range queries


/*==========================================================
8ï¸âƒ£ SCALABILITY & PERFORMANCE
==========================================================*/

-- Vertical Scaling:
-- Increase CPU, RAM
-- Limited & expensive

-- Horizontal Scaling:
-- Add more machines
-- More scalable

-- Sharding:
-- Split data across servers
-- Used in large databases


/*==========================================================
9ï¸âƒ£ DATA INTEGRITY & SECURITY
==========================================================*/

-- Data Integrity:
-- Accuracy & consistency of data

-- Constraints:
-- NOT NULL
-- UNIQUE
-- PRIMARY KEY
-- FOREIGN KEY
-- CHECK

-- RBAC (Role Based Access Control):
-- Access based on roles (Admin, User)

-- Encryption:
-- Convert data into unreadable format
-- Protects sensitive data

